{
  "text": "Use of rhTSH to provide TSH stimulation exogenously avoids many of these drawbacks [CITATION_1] ). Based on multicenter prospective studies [CITATION_2] , Haugen et al. 1999 [CITATION_3] , rhTSH was licensed in Europe as an adjunct to diagnostic WBS or serum Tg testing in 1999 and to radioiodine ablation in early 2005, in the US, it is licensed only in the diagnostic setting. However, in both settings, the licensing covers only adults (age \u2021 18 years), thus rhTSH administration in children is 'offlabel.' This is probably due to the lack of pediatric patients in reported series [CITATION_4] -to our knowledge, the youngest published rhTSH ablation patient was age 17 years. In adults, the recommended regimen is two consecutive daily intramuscular injections of 0.9 mg, followed by the ablative radioiodine activity 24 h later.",
  "correct_citation": {
